1. System Goal

A game economy fails when tokens only enter circulation but never return to sinks.

A sustainable system requires a closed velocity loop where tokens continuously cycle:

Reward → Spend → Burn → Re-inject

Most crypto games implement only the reward side, which causes inflation and collapse.

The correct structure is the Three-Velocity Loop Model.

2. The Three Token Loops

A stable game token must move through three distinct economic circuits.

Loop A — Extraction (Creation Layer)

Tokens enter circulation.

Sources:

mining

quests

AI rewards

battle prizes

exploration

Example:

Mountain mining → player receives D3X
AI loses battle → prize paid

Key rule:

Extraction must be controlled

Typical emission:

0.2% – 0.6% of supply per day

Confidence: 0.83

Loop B — Consumption (Utility Layer)

Tokens are spent inside the world.

Examples:

crafting weapons

repairing drones

entering battles

upgrading AI

building structures

travel cost

marketplace fees

This is where velocity happens.

Example flow:

player mines → earns 100 D3X
player upgrades drone → spends 80 D3X

Without this layer the token becomes a speculation asset, not a game currency.

Confidence: 0.91

Loop C — Destruction (Sink Layer)

Tokens permanently leave circulation.

Mechanisms:

burn from AI battles

crafting burn

upgrade burn

territory war burn

failed missions burn

repair burn

Example:

Drone destroyed → 30 D3X burned

This stabilizes supply.

Confidence: 0.92

3. The Missing Fourth Element

Many systems miss the Reinjection Layer.

Some burned or spent tokens should be reintroduced by the system.

Example:

Treasury collects:

marketplace fees
battle fees
crafting taxes

Treasury redistributes:

season rewards
leaderboards
AI funding
special events

This prevents liquidity starvation.

Confidence: 0.86

